type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Southern French: variant of   St  .   Romain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Romain","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Altagrace, Aurore, Camille, Dominique, Edele, Georges, Henri, Jacques, Jean-Marie, Jean-Michel, Jeanmarie.","French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and English: variant of   Roman  ."]}]},{"name":"Omer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Ahmed, Mohamed, Mohammed, Tarig, Mohammad, Murad, Abdirahman, Abdul, Abdulla, Abdulrahim, Ali, Amin.","Muslim: variant of   Omar  .","German: variant of   Ohmer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Omar","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammed, Mohamed, Ali, Omar, Ahmed, Ahmad, Hassan, Abdul, Husam, Khalid, Mohammad, Mohd.","Muslim: from the Arabic personal name <i>Omar</i> of uncertain etymology, found almost exclusively among Sunni Muslims. It is thought to be related to Arabic <i>ʿāmir</i> ‘prosperous, full of life, large, substantial’ (see   Amir   2). The root word <i>ʿumr</i> means ‘life’. ʿUmar bin al-Khaṭṭāb was the second of the ‘rightly guided’ caliphs (ruled 634–44); he was known by the title <i>al-Fārūq</i> ‘the distinguisher’, i.e. one who distinguishes between truth and falsehood. Compare   Omer   and   Umar  .","Catalan: topographic name for someone who lived by a group of elm trees, from the collective form of <i>om</i> ‘elm’."]}]},{"name":"Edmund","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protector’. It was borne by several early royal and saintly figures, including a 9th-century king of East Anglia killed by invading Danes, allegedly for his adherence to Christianity. In the 16th and 17th centuries, there was a good deal of interchange between <i>Edmund</i> and <i>Edward</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":34,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Edmund de St Omer was born in 1348, in Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, England as the son of Thomas de St Omer. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1392, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1348–1392":"1348–1392","1374–1420":"1374–1420","1320–1365":"1320–1365","1348":"1348","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, England":"Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, England","Mulbarton, Norfolk, England":"Mulbarton, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1348–1392":"1348–1392","1374–1420":"1374–1420","1320–1365":"1320–1365","1348":"1348","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, England":"Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, England","Mulbarton, Norfolk, England":"Mulbarton, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1348–1392":"1348–1392","1374–1420":"1374–1420","1320–1365":"1320–1365","1348":"1348","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, England":"Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, Angleterre","Mulbarton, Norfolk, England":"Mulbarton, Norfolk, Angleterre","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Edmund de St Omer est né en 1348, à Burnham Thorpe, Norfo